## Important database rule

Add a unique constraint so one relationship cannot be inserted many times accidentally:

```java
@Table(
    name = "person_sales_point_relationships",
    uniqueConstraints = @UniqueConstraint(
        name = "uk_person_sales_point_relationship",
        columnNames = {
            "person_user_id",
            "sales_point_id",
            "relationship_type"
        }
    )
)
```

Then AS400 retrying the same snapshot does not create duplicate rows.

## One thing to clarify before coding

Your `UserEntity.userId` is unique, and your relationship uses `personUserId`.

For the AS400 integration, decide clearly:

```text
userId = GPS group number
```

or:

```text
userId = generated Partner Repository identifier
gpsGroupNumber = separate external matching field
```

I recommend the second option:

```text
userId          = your internal stable Partner Repository identifier
gpsGroupNumber  = stable identifier received from AS400
```

Then find users during sync using:

```java
Optional<UserEntity> findByGpsGroupNumber(String gpsGroupNumber);
```

This is safer if future internal user-ID formatting changes.

